## 📖 The Data Flow Story (End-to-End)

### Act 1: The Shipment Begins

> 25 trucks depart from cities across India — Chennai, Delhi, Mumbai, Bangalore — carrying vaccines, seafood, dairy, frozen meat, and more. Each truck has 4 sensors streaming data every 2 seconds.

**What happens technically:**
- [shipment_factory.py](file:///Users/tarunsingh/Desktop/hackathon/hack/sim/shipment_factory.py) creates 25 shipments with pre-configured scenarios
- Each shipment has origin/destination cities, product type, cargo value, and safe temperature ranges
- Temperature ranges come from the **SOP document** (single source of truth) via [sop_parser.py](file:///Users/tarunsingh/Desktop/hackathon/hack/sop_parser.py)
- 4 simulator threads start publishing to MQTT topics: `livecold/temp`, `livecold/gps`, `livecold/reefer`, `livecold/door`

### Act 2: The Brain Processes

> Every 2 seconds, the pipeline receives ~100 sensor readings. Before any decision is made, each reading passes through a 4-layer anomaly filter. Only clean, verified data reaches the risk model.

**What happens technically:**
- [livecold_pipeline.py](file:///Users/tarunsingh/Desktop/hackathon/hack/pipeline/livecold_pipeline.py) subscribes to all MQTT topics
- Temperature readings hit the **Anomaly Detector** first (4 layers — see Section below)
- Clean readings enter the **Risk Model** (sigmoid-based probability calculation)
- Risk + cargo value feed into the **Diversion Optimizer** (cost vs. loss analysis)
- The final decision (CONTINUE / DIVERT) is published to `livecold/decisions`

### Act 3: The Diversion Decision

> SHP_3 is carrying ₹8 Lakh of dairy from Chennai to Bangalore. The temperature has crept to 9.2°C (safe max is 6°C). Risk probability hits 87%. The system calculates: continuing = ₹6.96L expected loss. Diverting to Coldstar Warehouse (42 km away, 38 min ETA) costs only ₹1,596. **Decision: DIVERT.**

**What happens technically:**
- [diversion_optimizer.py](file:///Users/tarunsingh/Desktop/hackathon/hack/decision_engine/diversion_optimizer.py) compares `expected_loss_continue` vs `total_divert_cost`
- [hub_manager.py](file:///Users/tarunsingh/Desktop/hackathon/hack/hub_manager.py) finds the nearest hub that: (a) is available, (b) has the right temp zone, (c) has capacity, (d) has the shortest traffic-aware ETA
- A diversion order is published to `livecold/divert`
- The GPS simulator receives it and physically re-routes the truck toward the hub
- WhatsApp notification is sent to the driver with hub name, Google Maps link, ETA, and contact number

### Act 4: The Dashboard Displays It All

> The operations manager sees everything in real-time: 25 trucks on a live map, alerts flashing red for critical shipments, SOP recommendations auto-generated by AI, carbon credits accumulating, and financial savings tracking.

